The influence under which this tendency grew up in Lucar is not far to seek: it is simply the school rhetoric. One ha* only to read a few pages of the suasoriae of the elder Seneca which are simply a collection of flowers of antithetical language to see this, which is first an ornament of style and thena disease, in its full glory. lt suited well the pedantic distinc· tions of the Stoics, and accordingly we find it dominant iu the writings of the younger Seneca, who with free use of anti· thesis dilutes Stoic philosophy into sermons. And thus it came to Lucan both by school training and by family tradition.
